SIMPLE: suppress
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suppress
<hw>Sup*press"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Suppressed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Suppressing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>suppressus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>supprimere</ets> to suppress;
<ets>sub</ets> under + <ets>premere</ets>, <ets>pressum</ets>, to press.
See <er>Sub-</er>, and <er>Press</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
overpower and crush; to subdue; to put down; to quell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every rebellion, when it is <qex>suppressed</qex>, doth make the
subject weaker, and the prince stronger.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To keep in; to restrain from utterance or vent;
<as>as, to <ex>suppress</ex> the voice; to <ex>suppress</ex> a
smile</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To retain without disclosure; to conceal; not to
reveal; to prevent publication of; <as>as, to <ex>suppress</ex>
evidence; to <ex>suppress</ex> a pamphlet; to <ex>suppress</ex> the
truth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>suppresses</qex> the name, and this keeps him in a
pleasing suspense.</q> <rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To stop; to restrain; to arrest the discharges of;
<as>as, to <ex>suppress</ex> a diarrhea, or a hemorrhage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To repress; restrain; put down; overthrow;
overpower; overwhelm; conceal; stifle; stop; smother.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suppressible</ent>⟦br⟧
